zed anarchist movements together. Printers and presses did more than report on the movement; they were constitutive of it, and their vitality in anarchist communities helps explain anarchism’s remarkable persistence in the face of continuous harassment, arrest, assault, deportation, and exile. By inquiring into the political, material, and aesthetic practices of anarchist print culture, Ferguson points to possible methods for cultivating contemporary political resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAnarchafeminism. 0aAnarchismxHistoryy20th centuryzEngland. 0aAnarchismxHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 0aAnarchismzEnglandxHistoryy20th century. 0aAnarchismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPress, AnarchistxHistoryy20th centuryzEngland. 0aPress, AnarchistxHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 0aPress, AnarchistzEnglandxHistoryy20th century. 0aPress, AnarchistzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadicalism and the press. 0aWomen's bookstores. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023869?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023869/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles